  "method": "We propose Adaptive-Depth Decoding (ADD), a multi-exit generative model that decides, per token, how many layers to evaluate before committing the next symbol. We attach lightweight vocabulary heads to a subset of decoder layers (e.g., every 2–4 blocks). During decoding, the model advances layer-by-layer and, at each potential exit, computes a compact set of gating features: (1) saturation via cosine similarity between the current hidden state and the previous layer’s state (and/or an EMA of deeper states), (2) predictive confidence from the current exit head (max-prob margin or entropy), and (3) cross-exit agreement (e.g., JS divergence between the last two exit distributions). A small halting module consumes these features and either exits early (skipping the remaining layers for this token) or continues deeper. A per-step decay schedule makes the halting criterion stricter for earlier tokens and more permissive later in the sequence, reflecting that early context typically benefits from more compute.\n\nTraining aligns intermediate exits to the full-depth model to avoid quality loss. First, apply deep supervision and distillation: each exit head minimizes a cross-entropy to ground truth and a KL-to-final-layer logits on teacher-forced text, ensuring shallow exits emulate the final model. Next, build a halting dataset by running the full-depth model on a corpus and retrospectively labeling, for each token and exit layer, the earliest “safe” exit that matches the final token and stays within a small log-prob KL/margin tolerance. Train the halting module to predict safe-exit decisions from its features. Finally, optionally fine-tune the halting policy with a lightweight RL phase that trades accuracy for compute: define an outcome reward based on sequence/task quality (e.g., BLEU or log-likelihood vs. full-depth) and a process reward based on calibrated confidence/consistency at the chosen exit; optimize expected reward minus a per-layer cost with a KL regularizer that keeps the policy close to the supervised halting baseline.\n\nAt inference, ADD proceeds progressively through layers for each token, evaluating the halting module after each exit head. If the predicted error risk falls below a token-position–dependent threshold, the model exits and emits the token using the current head; otherwise it evaluates more layers. To meet a target average compute budget without sacrificing quality on hard tokens, ADD adapts thresholds online with a simple PI controller: when recent average layers per token exceed the budget, it tightens thresholds slightly; when under budget, it relaxes them, while always honoring a maximum-risk cap learned during training. As an additional safeguard, a “verify-once” check triggers a one-time continuation to the next exit if the selected token’s margin is low or violates easy constraints (e.g., grammar/JSON format), preventing rare shallow mistakes from propagating.\n\nThis design yields substantial speedups because most easy tokens exit after few layers, while difficult tokens naturally consume more depth. Quality is preserved by: (i) distilling strong token distributions into intermediate exits, (ii) using saturation, confidence, and agreement together as robust evidence to stop, (iii) a conservative, decayed halting schedule early in sequences, and (iv) optional RL fine-tuning with KL control to favor compute savings only where they do not change model behavior.",
  "rationale": "Token difficulty varies widely across positions and prompts; fixed-depth decoding wastes compute on easy steps and starves hard ones. ADD allocates depth adaptively using signals that correlate with “no further change” if we were to evaluate more layers: cross-layer hidden-state saturation, high-confidence predictions, and cross-exit agreement. Distillation ensures shallow exits are competent proxies for the final layer, so exiting early does not degrade quality. The decayed schedule over time steps and a budget-aware threshold controller stabilize both quality and latency across sequences.\n\nThe optional RL phase turns halting into an explicit policy-optimization problem with a composite reward, letting the system discover where extra layers matter for task outcomes while a KL penalty anchors it to the supervised, high-fidelity baseline. Together, these components produce a compute-adaptive generator that preserves output quality while achieving sizable end-to-end speedups.",
