  "method": "We propose Adaptive Difficulty-Gated Decoding (ADGD), a two-stage, budgeted decoding scheme that allocates variable compute per token without sacrificing quality. At each time step, the model first runs a shallow prefix of layers to produce intermediate states and logits. A lightweight difficulty predictor attached to this shallow state estimates whether the next token is \"easy\" (safe to accept with little or no additional computation) or \"hard\" (merits extra reasoning or verification). Easy tokens are emitted early, while hard tokens trigger a localized refinement routine that expends more compute only where it is needed.\n\nThe difficulty predictor is a compact uncertainty head that consumes the shallow hidden state plus the preliminary next-token distribution, and outputs a calibrated confidence for the top-1 choice along with a \"need-more-compute\" score. To keep it fast and robust, the head learns a prototype-enhanced latent representation to sharpen class separation and is trained to predict full-depth correctness and margin (e.g., via a focal/contrastive loss against the full-stack model’s outcome). Thresholds for early acceptance are temperature-scaled and adjusted online to meet a target average compute budget (e.g., average layers per token), using a simple controller that raises the threshold if recent errors increase or lowers it if the budget allows more savings.\n\nFor hard tokens, ADGD invokes a local refinement module: generate a small candidate set (e.g., top-k from the shallow pass), then run a verifier that performs few, directed pairwise comparisons to settle the winner in O(k) compute. Concretely, we apply right-to-left passes that only compare adjacent candidates with a pairwise preference head; if the verifier’s final confidence clears a calibrated margin, we emit the chosen token. If not, we escalate selectively: either deepen to the full stack for that step or run one additional refinement pass that updates features with extra layers for the candidates only. As a safety net, extremely uncertain cases fall back to the standard full-depth, single-candidate decode for that step.\n\nADGD is deployed online and maintains causality: each token’s shallow pass is computed once, with KV caches reused. The controller enforces a global budget target (e.g., average 0.6× full layers per token) while monitoring a small held-out stream or rolling estimates of next-token accuracy; if any drift appears, thresholds tighten automatically. Because all aggressive paths are guarded by calibrated accept/reject tests and a guaranteed fall-back to the full-depth path, ADGD preserves or improves quality while substantially reducing average per-token compute.",
  "rationale": "Token difficulty is highly non-uniform: many positions (e.g., function words, syntactic closures, predictable continuations) can be decided confidently with partial computation, while others (e.g., rare entities, code identifiers, coreference-sensitive spots) benefit from added deliberation. ADGD exploits this by combining a fast, well-calibrated uncertainty estimate with a localized refinement routine that spends more compute only on hard tokens. The refinement uses efficient pairwise comparisons on a tiny candidate set, avoiding expensive full re-scoring of all alternatives.\n\nQuality is preserved through three safeguards: calibrated acceptance thresholds learned against the full-depth model; a verifier that makes relative (pairwise) judgments rather than over-trusting its own absolute scores; and a guaranteed fall-back to the standard, full-compute path when uncertainty remains high. A lightweight controller ensures the system meets a desired average compute budget while reacting to shifts in difficulty, maintaining both efficiency and reliability.",
